# Global configuration params
IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH = 224, 224
SEED = 420
BATCH_SIZE = 32
CLASS_NAMES = ['Apples', 'Tomatoes']
train_dir = "./example_training_data"
test_dir = "./test_data"

(training_data, validation_data) = tf.keras.utils.image_dataset_from_directory(
  train_dir,
  validation_split=0.1,
  subset="both",
  labels='inferred',  
  seed=SEED,
  image_size=(IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH),
  batch_size=BATCH_SIZE)

test_data = tf.keras.utils.image_dataset_from_directory(
    test_dir,
    labels='inferred',
    seed=SEED,
    image_size=(IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH),
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE)

def show_images(images, labels, class_names, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    plt.title(title)
    for i in range(4):
        plt.subplot(2, 2, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(images[i].numpy().astype("uint8"))
        plt.title(class_names[labels[i]])
        plt.axis("off")

for image_batch, label_batch in training_data.take(1):  
    show_images(image_batch, label_batch, training_data.class_names, "Training")

for image_batch, label_batch in test_data.take(1):  
    show_images(image_batch, label_batch, test_data.class_names, "Test")

# Simple cnn example
def create_simple_cnn():
    model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Rescaling(1./255),
        tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH, 3)),
        tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(),
        tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
        tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(),
        tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(2)
    ])
    return model

# Use MobileNetV2 model
def create_mobilenetv2():
    base_model = tf.keras.applications.MobileNetV2(input_shape=(IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH, 3),
                                                   include_top=False,
                                                   weights='imagenet')
    base_model.trainable = False  
    model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Rescaling(1./255),
        base_model,
        tf.keras.layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(2)
    ])
    return model

Training and Evaluating¶

In [78]:
# Compile and train the model
def compile_and_train(model, training_data, validation_data, epochs, optimizer):
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizer,
                  loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    history = model.fit(training_data, epochs=epochs, validation_data=validation_data)
    return history

def evaluate_and_plot_metrics(model, history, test_data):
    # Evaluation
    test_loss, test_accuracy = model.evaluate(test_data)
    true_labels = []
    predicted_probs = []

    for images, labels in test_data:
        probs = model.predict(images)
        predicted_probs.extend(probs)
        true_labels.extend(labels.numpy())

    # Convert to numpy arrays
    true_labels = np.array(true_labels)
    predicted_probs = np.array(predicted_probs)
    predicted_labels = np.argmax(predicted_probs, axis=1)

    # Confusion Matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(true_labels, predicted_labels)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=plt.cm.Blues)
    plt.colorbar()

    tick_marks = np.arange(len(CLASS_NAMES))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, CLASS_NAMES, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, CLASS_NAMES)
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')
    plt.ylabel('True Label')
    
    # Adding annotations to each cell with the count
    for i in range(cm.shape[0]):
        for j in range(cm.shape[1]):
            plt.text(j, i, cm[i, j], ha="center", va="center", color="black")
    
    plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
    plt.show()

    # ROC curve and AUC
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(true_labels, predicted_probs[:, 1])
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange', lw=2, label=f'ROC curve (area = {roc_auc:.2f})')
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC)')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()

    # Plot the loss over epochs
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label='Training Loss')
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='Validation Loss')
    plt.title('Model Loss Over Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.legend(loc="upper right")
    plt.show()

    # Print the AUC
    print(f"AUC: {roc_auc:.4f}")
    
    # Print loss and accuracy
    print(f"Test Loss: {test_loss}, Test Accuracy: {test_accuracy}")

# Test function for models   
def run(create_model_function, epochs = 5, optimizer = 'adam'):     
    created_model = create_model_function()
    
    history = compile_and_train(created_model, training_data, validation_data, epochs, optimizer)
    evaluate_and_plot_metrics(created_model, history, test_data)
    
    return created_model

Running tests¶

Using different learning strategies:

  • faster decay of learning rate => how does it affect the loss rate?
  • 3 models, with increasingly higher decay rate of the learning rate Using different CNNs
  • Custom simple CNN with scaling and few layers
  • MobileNetV2

Models:

  • Model11/Model21 => default optimizer (adam)
  • Model12/Model22 => adam with learning rate 0.001 and decay rate 0.00001
  • Model13/Model23 => adam with learning rate 0.001 and decay rate 0.0001
  • Model14 => adam with learning rate 0.0001 and decay rate 0.001

Results:

  • Almost no difference between model11, model12 and model13, all of them instantly drop to ~1,1.5 loss rate after the first epoch
    • Test with new model14 (higher base learning rate and higher decay) => for some reason validation loss sometimes goes up => not good!
  • More noticeable difference between model21 and model22, but almost not noticeable difference after that (model22 vs model23).
  • Our model22 optimizer performs better than the default Adam optimizer with an AuC up to 94%
  • MobileNet models perform better on average, but are also more heavy weight to train and predict
  • Modifying the learning rate has a great impact on the result, causing the model to overshoot the optimum or get stuck

Loading and inferring new data¶

Using the simple CNN, inference classifies the two images incorrectly (AuC is around ~60% here). Inference using the models with MobileNetV2 classifies the two images correctly (although lower %) (~90% AuC here). The images were hand-drawn and chosen randomly and are not included in the training or test.

In [121]:
m_loaded = tf.keras.models.load_model("models/m22")
inference_dir = './inference'

# Load all images and predict classes
images = []
predictions = []
confidences = []

for filename in os.listdir(inference_dir):
    if filename.endswith('.png'):
        img_path = os.path.join(inference_dir, filename)
        img = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.load_img(img_path, target_size=(IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH))
        img_array = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.img_to_array(img)
        img_array = tf.expand_dims(img_array, 0)  

        # Make a prediction
        prediction = m_loaded.predict(img_array)
        score = tf.nn.softmax(prediction[0])

        images.append(img)
        predictions.append(np.argmax(score)) # Get best prediction
        confidences.append(100 * np.max(score))

# Display the images with predictions
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
for i in range(len(images)):
    plt.subplot(1, len(images), i + 1)
    plt.imshow(images[i])
    plt.title(f"{CLASS_NAMES[predictions[i]]}\n{confidences[i]:.2f}%")
    plt.axis('off')
plt.show()
